stratified.holdout <- function(y, ptr)
{
  n <- length(y)
  labels <- unique(y)       # Obtain classifiers
  id.tr <- id.te <- NULL
  # Loop once for each unique label value
  
  y <- sample(sample(sample(y)))
  
  for(j in 1:length(labels)) 
  {
    sj <- which(y==labels[j])  # Grab all rows of label type j  
    nj <- length(sj)           # Count of label j rows to calc proportion below
    
    id.tr <- c(id.tr, (sample(sample(sample(sj))))[1:round(nj*ptr)])
  }                               # Concatenates each label type together 1 by 1
  
  id.te <- (1:n) [-id.tr]          # Obtain and Shuffle test indices to randomize                                
  
  return(list(idx1=id.tr,idx2=id.te)) 
}  



hold  <- stratified.holdout(train_lb_71, 0.1) 
id.tr <- hold$idx1
ntr   <- length(id.tr)

p   <- ncol(xtrain)


hold  <- stratified.holdout(test_lb_71, 0.1)

### Question 1.4 Identify two false positives and two false negatives at the test phase, and in each case, plot the true image against its falsely predicted counterpart.

# Function to display images
display_images <- function(indices, labels) {
  par(mfrow=c(3,3))
  for (j in 1:9) {
    i <- indices[j]
    image(1:28, 1:28, matrix(xte[i,], nrow=28)[ , 28:1], 
          col = gray(seq(0, 1, 0.05)), xlab = "", ylab="")
    title(paste("True Label:", labels[i]))
  }
}

Exercise 2. Investigating the Bayes risk R*is Regression

# 2.1 Let n = 99. Generate {(Xi, Yi), i = 1, · · · , n}, an iid sample of size n where each (Xi, Yi) as density p(x, y)
N<-99
Xi<-runif(N,0,2*pi)
Yi<-rnorm(N,mean=pi/2*Xi + 3/4 *pi*cos(pi/2 * (1+Xi)),sd=3/pi)
plot(Xi,Yi,pch=20,col="slateblue4",main="Scatter plot of normally distributed data")

library(caret)
## Warning: package 'caret' was built under R version 4.3.2
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Loading required package: lattice
library(rpart)
library(ggplot2)
Error_matrix=matrix(0, nrow = 100, ncol = 4)
for (i in 1:100){
  x=runif(99, 0, 2*pi)
  y=rnorm(99, pi*x/2+3*pi*cos(pi/2*(1+x))/4, 3/pi)
  Datafram_x_y= cbind(x,y)
  sample = sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(Datafram_x_y), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.6,0.4))
  Train_set=data.frame(Datafram_x_y[sample,])
  Data_set=data.frame(Datafram_x_y[!sample,])
  
  ### a) KNN
  model_KNN=knnreg(y~x, data=Train_set)
  x=Data_set[,2]
  model_Pred_KNN=predict(model_KNN,data.frame(x))
  Error_matrix[i,1]=mean((x-model_Pred_KNN)^2)
  
  ### B) Linear regression
  model_LINM=lm(y~x,data=Train_set)
  x=Data_set[,2]
  model_Pred_LINM=predict(model_LINM,data.frame(x))
  Error_matrix[i,2]=mean((x-model_Pred_LINM)^2)
  
  ### C) Polynomial Regression
  model_PLYN=lm(y~poly(x,1), data =Train_set)
  x=Data_set[,2]
  model_Pred_LINM=predict(model_PLYN,data.frame(x))
  Error_matrix[i,3]=mean((x- model_Pred_LINM)^2)
  
  ### D) Regression tree learner
  model_REGTR=rpart(y~x, data=Train_set)
  x=Data_set[,2]
  model_Pred_REGTR=predict(model_REGTR,data.frame(x))
  Error_matrix[i,4]=mean((x-model_Pred_REGTR)^2)
}
boxplot(Error_matrix, main = "Box plot for the error matrix")

title=c("kNN","Linear", "Polynomial","Tree learner")
errodata=data.frame(data=Error_matrix)
names(errodata)=title
boxplot(errodata, las=1, col ="skyblue4",main="Box plot of test error")

# Loop through each randomly selected variable
for (variable in random_variables) {
  # Check if the variable is numeric
  if (is.numeric(DNA[[variable]])) {
    # Plot histogram for numeric variables
    hist(DNA[[variable]], main = paste("Histogram of", variable), xlab = variable, col = "green", border = "brown", breaks = "FD")
  } else {
    # Plot bar plot for categorical variables
